(1877, 1, '2014-06-02 12:55:07', '2014-06-02 12:55:07', 'Ok, so this is my first post… What better way to begin than discussing two of my favourite topics. Cycling, technology, specifically cycling technology. I might just blog about technology, but the truth is I find the useful application of technology much more exciting!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_1873" align="alignnone" width="1100"]<a href="http://wizard.technology/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Test-on-Bike-cr.jpg"><img src="http://wizard.technology/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Test-on-Bike-cr1.jpg" alt="Test on bike" width="1100" height="600" class="size-full wp-image-1873" /></a> Source: http://www.vo2test.com/assets/Test-on-Bike.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\nThose of you who know me are well aware of my tendency to go on a bit about my cycling – I’m not the type of cyclist who rides through red lights or is aggressive towards other road users – no – I’m the sort who believes that every road user has the right to be there and wants to go about their business whatever it might be. That’s just a bit of background – the new breed of cyclist, of which there seem to be millions is perhaps the subject of another post… I’ve always been a cyclist (apart from an eight year break straight after I attended training camp in Majorca [that’s just how sore I was!]), and like most of my peers – and I’ve always wanted anything that will make me go faster. Ever since BBC’s ‘Tomorrows World’ I’ve always been very interested about any kind of bleeding edge technology. I purchased a set of Tri-Bars the weekend after they were deemed legal by the CTT or RTTC as it was then. Cyclists are suckers for shiny new bits that bring promise of going faster than their competitors (this often includes their riding partners – if they have a competitive streak like myself).\r\n\r\nBack then only [sport] scientists with access to expensive monitoring equipment, but recently the cost of measuring equipment, specifically power meters (roughly speaking a device that measures the force applied to the pedals, and multiplies it by the angular velocity to arrive at a figure described in Watts)  has dropped to a price which falls within the budget of many amateur cyclists, and can be fitted to the bicycle itself rather than being restricted to the lab. \r\n\r\nSome may say I’m boring, but ever since college I’ve been interested in data – not just data, but how to build information from data. Data is (or ‘are’ if we are talking plural units) normally fairly meaningless to the naked eye, it’s how we format it that transforms it into useful information. Cycling is one of the few sports where we can gather so much useful data – the bicycle is an extremely efficient machine where many measurements can be taken in addition to the standard metrics such as heart rate which can be measured in many other endurance sports.  There are many desktop and web-based programs out there which allow the cyclist to view various metrics in a graphical format. These are highly useful for post race analysis, or monitoring training loads etc. Some have highly useable, convenient, social web-based interfaces but don’t show enough data (Strava), others have ugly interfaces with poor user experience, but are much better at showing performance trends (WKO+). The result is usually that rides have to be uploaded to several systems. \r\n\r\nBut the question is do any of systems help the average user? Top time triallist and author  Michael Hutchinson’s book Faster: The Obsession, Science and Luck Behind the World''s Fastest Cyclists  describes how the success of the British Cycling Team was partly founded on the use  technology – coaches using vast amounts of historical data to produce training plans for their athletes. This is where I think where the data recorded is particularly useful. It’s interpretation. I think the recent results on the track speak for themselves.\r\n\r\nI have been using a power meter for over 18 months now, in which time I have become slower and slower in my races. In 2012 my target was to go under the hour for a 25 Mile time trial, something I had spent the whole winter training for – using some rollers (basically a treadmill for a bike) trying to spin a bigger and bigger gear, and doing some MTB and club road rides. As I’d injured myself late 2011 season, I’d had to start gingerly, so had to rapidly gain fitness in time for the start of my racing season in March. It was all very unscientific, but the long and short of it was that by June, on a wet and windy day I managed to do a 59:32, achieving my target. Unfortunately, I have no idea what power I’d produced on that day as I didn’t take delivery of my first power meter until Jan 2013. With all the live monitoring and analysis that a power meter provides 2013 was a much slower year, I’d also read many books by respected authors on the subject too – late 2013 I’d decided to ignore all I’d read and go back to training by  feel, but using a power meter to measure for improvement.\r\n\r\n2014  began ok again but by May I seemed to be finishing well further back than I know I’m capable of – I’m only 2 Watts behind my best performance of 2013, but feeling a bit fed up. Recently at my local cycling club’s  (Minehead CC) first of the year’s hill climb series, We had a debate whether technology actually helps. One of the club’s members does not subscribe to the hi-tech route – rather than ‘All the gear, no idea’ it’s ‘None of the gear, definitely doing something right’, as he frequently rides much, much faster than his lycra’d up counterparts – I love to see this, unless, it is me he is overtaking of course! He is a farmer who admits to like eating greasy food, but for whatever reason, he is incredibly fast, and a top bloke too! His training consists of a greasy fry up and going out for a ride to enjoy himself… I can’t help but think what he would be like if incorporated high-tech cycling into his world – perhaps he would just give up due to the boredom of spending hundreds of hours riding a stationary bike though the winter.\r\n\r\nAttending races frequently, I still feel the hi-tech route is the way to go, but the danger is not knowing how to interpret the information, despite having over 20years of competitive riding experience (in fits and starts) – I’m still failing at this. I also feel training without any formal coaching is bad too – many top coaches insist that their athletes own and use a power meter. A self-coached athlete is a danger to themselves. Recently I’ve started to use TrainerRoad software which is like being coached in a way, but does not take into account individual strengths and weaknesses, but at least this formalised high tech training is guaranteed to bring improved results. \r\nMy take on it is that the cyclist should be able to look for patterns in their training and race data that lead up to their best performances, rather than relying on rule or algorithm based analysis. We’re going to be creating an online app that allows the user to do this. No details yet, but harnessing the power of HTML5 we’re going to be filling in the gaps left my other applications.  A good place to look is the feature request boards – It seems as if I am one of the frustrated many who have specific common requests that just don’t get implemented. No names mentioned…\r\n\r\n<aside class="further-reading">\r\nRecommended further reading:\r\n<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Faster-Obsession-Science-Fastest-Cyclists-ebook/dp/B00IUMCCUG/" title="Faster: The Obsession, Science and Luck Behind the World''s Fastest Cyclists" target="_blank">Faster: The Obsession, Science and Luck Behind the World''s Fastest Cyclists.</a> Michael Hutchinson\r\n<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/High-Tech-Cycling-Edmund-Burke/dp/0736045074/" title="High Tech Cycling" target="_blank">High Tech Cycling [Paperback]</a> 2nd Ed. Edmund R. Burke\r\n<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Training-Racing-Power-Meter-2nd-ebook/dp/B007WZ55XI/" title="Training and Racing with a Power Meter, 2nd Ed." target="_blank">Training and Racing with a Power Meter</a>, 2nd Ed. by Hunter Allen and Coggan, Andy , PhD (1 Apr 2010)\r\n</aside>\r\n', 'Do we need High Tech Cycling Technology?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1814-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-02 12:55:07', '2014-06-02 12:55:07', '', 1814, 'http://wizard.technology/1814-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
